snippet.textDisplay: The test is free but how much does the treatment cost? What if a lot of people can't afford the treatment? A chain is only as strong as its weakest link. A society is only as healthy as it's most unhealthy person. If anyone is excluded from receiving a vaccine, or anti-biotic, our society will be vulnerable to whatever virus that person contracts. If 50%-60% of Americans cannot afford a $500 trip to the emergency room (we all know a trip to the emergency room costs many times more than $500), that means 50%-60% of Americans will likely not get tested because the result might land them in the emergency room. Or maybe much worse, they might end up hospitalized and be bankrupted by the insanely high cost of everything from treatment to drugs. Some hospitals charge upwards of $15,000 per night  just for the bed. Most Americans who work in the service and retail industries can't afford to be sick and miss work, meaning they will be at work even if they are sick. Everything they touch, breathe on, cough on, sneeze on, and everyone around them, are now at risk of being infected.We should all contribute to one another's health care costs because our own live's are at risk when people can't afford to go see a doctor If the president can suspend interest payments on student loans at a time when the world's markets are crashing should go to show everyone that we can afford to provide education for everyone and we can provide healthcare for all. If we don't provide a basic standard for higher education, and health care for everyone, the USA will continue to be dumber, fatter, and sicker than the rest  of  the world.
